{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox Stadium | stadium_name = Barbourfields Stadium | nickname = Emagumeni | image = | fullname = Barbourfields Stadium | location = [[Bulawayo]], Zimbabwe | coordinates = 20°07′51″S 28°34′11″E | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = Bulawayo City Council | operator = | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[Highlanders FC]] | seating_capacity = 40,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/cup_of_nations/2322767.stm|title=Clockwatch: African Nations Cup|date=12 October 2002|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> | dimensions = }}
'''Barbourfields Stadium''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Bulawayo]], Zimbabwe, home to Highlanders FC. It is currently used mostly for [[association football|football]] matches. It is owned by [[Bulawayo|Bulawayo City Council]] and is home to [[Highlanders F.C.]], one of the biggest soccer teams in Zimbabwe. Soccer fans commonly refer to the stadium as "Emagumeni" meaning "our backyard" in iSiNdebele. As of 2017, Barbourfields Stadium may be used as homeground to other football teams in and around Bulawayo including Bantu Rovers FC, How Mine FC and Chicken Inn FC, but mostly, when they play big teams. The stadium consists of four stands including the most famous ones; the Mpilo End (usually for the away fans), and, of coarse, the Soweto End (for the 'die hard' home fans). It has a capacity of 40,000<ref>http://www.worldstadiums.com/africa/countries/zimbabwe.shtm</ref> making it the second largest stadium in Zimbabwe after the National Sports Stadium (60,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highlandersfc.co.zw/TheClub/HomeStadiumEmagumeni/tabid/59/Default.aspx|title=www.highlandersfc.co.zw|publisher=}}</ref>
Highlanders F.C. drew the highest average home attendance in their domestic league in 2016, with an average attendance of 5,614. The previous year, they drew an average home attendance of 7,276 for domestic league games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.co.zw/fans-shun-psl-matches/|title=Fans shun PSL matches - The Chronicle|website=www.chronicle.co.zw}}</ref>
