{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}
The '''multiple offensive''' is an [[American football]] offensive scheme used by several teams in the [[National Football League]] and [[college football]]. It is a hybrid offense consisting of formations and plays from various other schemes including the [[pro-style offense]], [[spread offense]], and [[pistol offense]], and possibly more.

The multiple offense allows for a wide variety of play calls and formations, from spreading the field with 4 or 5 [[wide receivers]] to utilizing [[Fullback (gridiron football)|fullback]]s and [[tight end]]s to establish a power running game. As such, it can be adjusted to fit the skills of available offensive personnel and can be difficult for an opposing defense to scout and prepare for. On the other hand, it can result in an offense which is "mediocre at everything", especially in college football, where practice time is limited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingcharts.com/dictionary/nfl/multiple-offense.aspx |title=What is Multiple Offense? Definition from |publisher=SportingCharts.com |date= |accessdate=2015-08-12}}</ref><ref>https://www.footballstudyhall.com/2017/1/24/14376400/the-offense-formerly-known-as-pro-style-manball-florida-state-michigan</ref><ref>https://www.baltimoresportsandlife.com/mike-locksleys-multiple-offense/</ref>

